  1. User Interface Programs

     These programs are provided for the users to send their requests to the
     CRONO system. Each one has specific parameters. The requests are sent to
     the Access Manager, which evaluates each request, looks for access rights,
     checks the user command parameters and so on. The last program (crsetdef)
     was designed to make easier the utilization of the other user programs.

  
  1.0 amconf (-f option) (The administrator should take care about this file)

     Most commands described here uses the '-f' option. This option is used for
     the User Interface programs to know where is the file that defines the
     hostname and port for the Access Manager. The name of this file is amconf.
     Omitting the '-f' option, the User Interface programs will get the file
     specified at the CRONO's compilation time (so the administrator takes care
     about this).
     An example of the amconf file is:
     #################################################################
     # <hostname> <port>
     servername 7001
     #################################################################
     
     Probably the administrator has configured this file for the users,
     so if you're not the administrator don't worry about this file.


  1.1 cralloc (CRONO Allocate)

     Use this program to allocate nodes in a cluster. The parameters are the
     number of nodes, the time for allocation, the cluster name and the
     configuration file.

     Usage:
     As soon as possible:
        cralloc -c <cluster> -n <nodes> -t <time> [-s|-e] [ -b <bjscript> ]
          [ -f <file> ]

     At a given time:
        cralloc -c <cluster> -n <nodes> -it <itime> [ -t <time> | -ft <ftime> ]
          [-s|-e] [ -b <bjscript> ] [ -u <user> ] [ -f <file> ]

       cralloc --help

        -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
        -n <nodes>              : Number of nodes or
                                  a file to make qualitative allocation
        -t <time>               : Time of allocation in minutes
        -s                      : Shared access
        -e                      : Exclusive access
        -b <bjscript>           : Batch job script
        -it <itime>             : Initial Time (HH:MM[-dd[/mm[/yyyy]]])
        -ft <ftime>             : Final Time (HH:MM[-dd[/mm[/yyyy]]])
        -u <user>               : User Name (option only for root)
        -f <file>               : Configuration file
        --help                  : Display this help and exit

     Examples: cralloc -c cluster1 -n 3 -t 15 -e             (Interactive mode)
               cralloc -c cluster1 -n 3 -t 15 -e -b prog1.sh (Batch job mode)

               cralloc -c cluster1 -n 3 -it 20:00 -ft 20:15 -e (At a given time)
               cralloc -c cluster1 -n 3 -it 20:00 -t 2 -e (At a given time)

     If you want to make a qualitative allocation, that is, you want to
     choose the node types, you must create a file with the following syntax:
     <node type>:<number of nodes>
     <node type>:<number of nodes>
       ....

     For example:
     p3-550:4
     p4-2000:2

     And, use this file as the argument for -n option.
     Another option is specifying the node types without a file.
     For example:
       cralloc -n p3-550:2
          or
       cralloc -n "p3-550:4 p4-2000:2"

     Note that if you have more than one node type specify them within double 
     commas ("...").

     In order to discover the available node types, use the crinfo command.

     Important advise:
     If the crsetdef was used to set the "bjscript" parameter and
     a user wants to allocate the resources in interactive mode, the
     "bjscript" must be cleared (crsetdef -d bjscript).


  1.2 crrls (CRONO Release)

     This program allows to release nodes allocated by cralloc. Using this
     program, your nodes will be released and all your process executing will be
     finalized (if you have resources) or cancel a request (if you don't have
     resources).

     Usage: crrls -c <cluster> [ -rid <rid> ] [ -u <user> ] [ -f <file> ] 
       crrls --help

        -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
        -rid <rid>              : Request id (cancel a reserve)
        -u <user>               : User Name (option only for root)
        -f <file>               : Configuration file
        --help                  : Display this help and exit

     Example: crrls -c cluster1
              crrls -c cluster1 -rid 2

  1.3 crqview (CRONO Queue View)

     This program shows information about the requests queue, like user names,
     start and finish times of the users, the number of available nodes and the
     allocation type (exclusive or shared).

     Usage: crqview -c <cluster> [ -t ] [ -f <file> ]
             -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
             -t                      : Show node types information
             -f <file>               : Configuration file

     Example: crqview -c cluster1
              crqview -c cluster1 -t
     


  1.4 crnodes (CRONO Nodes)

     This program can be used to show the hostname of each node allocated by the
     cralloc command. Using the -s option, it is possible to show some
     additional information about the nodes. This command now has a flag (-w)
     which is used to show all the cluster nodes and who is using each of them.

     Usage: crnodes -c <cluster> [ -s "<sel> <sel> ... <sel>" ] [ -f <file> ]
     crnodes --help
     
        -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
        -s <sel>...             : Select nodes information
                                  (sel='nprocs','type','arch','desc' or 'all')
        -w                      : Show all cluster nodes and who is using
                                  each of them
        -f <file>               : Configuration file
        --help                  : Display this help and exit
 
     Example: crnodes -c cluster1
              crnodes -c cluster1 -s all
              crnodes -c cluster1 -s "type arch"
              crnodes -c cluster1 -w 
                                                                       

  1.5 crinfo (CRONO Information)

     Using this program, you can view information about the managed clusters.
     This information are access rights for allocations, cluster name, number of
     nodes, special periods and others.

     Usage: crinfo [ -c <cluster> || -all ] [ -f <file> ]

          -c <cluster> : Cluster name
          -all         : Show information about all clusters available (default)
          -f <file>    : Configuration file


     Examples: crinfo -c tropical
               crinfo -all

  1.6 crnmc (CRONO Node Manager Client)

     This program allows you to execute operation directly on the nodes
     allocated.
     The available operations are created by the Administrator and you can
     obtain them using the -v option.

     Usage: crnmc -c <cluster> -v [-f <file>] | -c <cluster> <-all> |
               -n <node1> <node2> ... > -op <operation> [-f <file>] | -mf <mach>

             -c <cluster>            : Cluster name
             -all                    : All allowed nodes
             -mf                     : Machine file
             -n                      : Nodes
             -op <operation>         : Operation to execute
             -v                      : View operations
             -f <file>               : Configuration file

     Example:
         crnmc -c cluster1 -all -op killp   #Kill processes of all allowed notes
                                             of a user
         crnmc -c cluster1 -n cluster1_01   #Kill processes just on cluster1_01
                                             node

  1.7 crsetdef (CRONO Set Defaults)

     The missing parameters (<cluster>,<time>,<nodes>,<share>,<bjscript>,
     <mpicomp>, <mpirun>, <arch>) of the above commands will be filled out using
     the default file.
     This program was made to allow you easily to modify the default
     configuration file ($HOME/.crono/defaults) without needing to edit it by
     hand.
     Its functions are:
          - show one or all keywords of the default configuration file.
          - set a new value for an existing keyword.
          - add or remove an entry in file.
          - create your personal definitions for specific use.

     Usage: crsetdef [ <keyword> [ <value> ] ] | -d <keyword> | --help
             <keyword>         : Shows the keyword from defaults file
             <keyword> <value> : If keyword exists, set a new value. If not,
                                 add a new entry in file
             -d <keyword>      : Remove the line that contains keyword

     In the usage, keyword and value mean:
           <keyword> is a string that contains a value associated.
           <value> is the value for a keyword specified.

     Examples: Assuming a typical default configuration file below:

           To show the definitions
           $ crsetdef
           CRONO definitions
           ===== ===========
           cluster=tropical
           time=15
           nodes=3
           shared=n
           bjscript=<empty>
           mpicomp=mpiethercc
           mpirun=mpiether


           To show an entry from file:
           $ crsetdef cluster

           To modify the value for the "time" keyword, type:
           $ crsetdef time 20

           To add an entry to the file, type:
           $ crsetdef something somevalue

           To remove an entry, type:
           $ crsetdef -d tmppath

     Please use this program to modify the defaults configuration file. If you
     decide to edit the file by hand, feel free. But in this case, take care with
     the correct sintax in each line, that must be <keyword>=<value> without the
     "<" and ">" signals.
     The keywords also must be in the start of each line.


