  2. How to Compile and Run Programs
   
  2.1 crcomp and crrun

  There are two wrapper scripts to help users to compile and run programs:
  crcomp and crrun. The first one is useful in environments which have more
  than one Mpi.
  So the Administrator defines, for example, the Mpi directories and you can
  choose one of the Mpi versions available. The second one is used to run
  programs. In this second script you have to specify the environment, the
  cluster, and optionality the architecture which will be used to run the
  programs.
  Below are just examples of the usage of these scripts.

  To compile: crcomp (CRONO Compiler)

  The user can specify if he/she wants an executable for a specific
  architecture or not. For this procedure the user can provide use the
  flag "-arch <arch_name>". Possible values for this flag are defined by the
  administrator. When the user doesn't specify this flag, it will be generated
  two executables for all the available architectures. In this case, one will
  add extension in the executable with the architecture names.
      
   Usage: crcomp -env <mpicomp> [ -arch <arch> ] [options]

   If -arch is not specified, one will compile for both architectures
  
   Ex1.: crcomp -env mpiethercc hello.c -o hello
   Ex2.: crcomp -env mpiethercc -arch ia64 hello.c -o hello


  To run: crrun (CRONO Runner)

  Usage: crrun -c <cluster> -env <mpirun> [-arch <arch> ] [options]
        
   If -arch is not specified, one will run on available architectures
        
   Ex1.: crrun -c amazonia -env mpiether -arch ia32 -np 8 hello
   Ex2.: crrun -c amazonia -env mpigm -np 16 multiply 20 30

  If the user has nodes of more than one architecture, crrun will look for the
  extensions of all architecture names (like ".ia32" and ".ia64").
  If the user doesn't want to use extensions, he/she can use the %a symbol,
  for example /home/stelmar/%a/myprog.

  When the user time starts, CRONO can create the machine files for all
  execution environments. Therefore the "-machinefile" parameter will not
  be used.
  To simplify the command line the user will pass just one "-np" and the
  crrun command will create more than one "-np" (if necessary).

  For example, suppose two machine files:
  - IA64 machines:
       amazonia01
       amazonia02

 - IA32 machines:
       amazonia03
       amazonia04
       amazonia05

  When the user gives "-np 3" crrun will create "-np 2" and "-np 1".
  When the user gives "-np 5" crrun will create "-np 2" and "-np 3".
  When the user gives "-np 7" crrun will create "-np 4" and "-np 3".
  When the user gives "-np 9" crrun will create "-np 4" and "-np 5".
  And so on.

  Note  that the "best" machines will be used before the others.
  In our case, the IA64 will be used before the iA32.

  The machine files are stored in:
     $HOME/.crono/machfile.<cluster>.<arch>.<environment>

  2.2 Defining the number of processes to execute for each node

    The administrator defines the number of processes that will be executed
  on each node (regarding the node type). Using the crinfo command you can
  view the definitions (nprocs variable).

  If you want to modify the default values you can create a file
  $HOME/.crono/nodetypes with following syntax:
  <nodetype>=<nprocs>
  <nodetype>=<nprocs>
    . . .

     Example:
               p3=4
               p4=8

  So, when your time starts, and the machine files are created, your values
  are considered.


  2.3 Batch jobs

  Batch jobs is a mechanism to submit user jobs automatically when the
  requested time starts. The resources will be released when the job or the
  user time finishes. There are some variables available to make the scripts:
     - CR_CLUSTER   = cluster name
     - CR_USERID    = user id
     - CR_USERNAME  = user name
     - CR_NODES     = list of user nodes (e.g. : "tropical01 tropical02")
     - CR_NODESINFO  = list of user nodes with additional information
          Format: (for each node)
             <hostname>:<nodetype>:<architecture>:
             <number of processes>:"<description>"<space>
     - CR_RID      = request id

  Example of a batch job script:

  #!/bin/sh
  #
  # Multiply matrix
  #########################################################################
  /usr/local/bin/crrun -c $CR_CLUSTER -np 16 mult_matrix
  /usr/local/bin/crrun -c $CR_CLUSTER -np 16 mult_matrix
  rm $HOME/tmp/*
  ########################################################################  

  An example of how to allocate the nodes using batch jobs:
  
  $ cralloc -c tropical -n 16 -t 15 -b mult_matrix.sh

  The batch job file can be a binary or a script file.
